# Code with Comments

```cpp
class Solution {
public:

    // DFS function
    void dfs(int row, int col,
             vector<vector<int>>& image,
             int oldColor,
             int newColor)
    {
        int n = image.size();
        int m = image[0].size();

        // Mark current cell as visited by changing its color
        image[row][col] = newColor;

        // Up, Down, Left, Right
        int dr[] = {-1, 1, 0, 0};
        int dc[] = {0, 0, -1, 1};

        // Check all 4 directions
        for(int i = 0; i < 4; i++)
        {
            int nr = row + dr[i];
            int nc = col + dc[i];

            // Skip if outside matrix
            if(nr < 0 || nr >= n || nc < 0 || nc >= m)
                continue;

            // Skip if color is different
            if(image[nr][nc] != oldColor)
                continue;

            // Visit neighbor
            dfs(nr, nc, image, oldColor, newColor);
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> floodFill(vector<vector<int>>& image,
                                  int sr,
                                  int sc,
                                  int newColor)
    {
        // Store original color
        int oldColor = image[sr][sc];

        // No work needed
        if(oldColor == newColor)
            return image;

        // Start DFS
        dfs(sr, sc, image, oldColor, newColor);

        return image;
    }
};
```

---

# Why No Visited Array?

Normally DFS uses:

```cpp
visited[n][m]
```

But here:

```cpp
image[row][col] = newColor;
```

already marks the cell as visited.

So a separate visited array is not required.

---

# Complexity

### Time

```cpp
O(N * M)
```

Every cell is visited at most once.

### Space

```cpp
O(N * M)
```

Worst-case recursion stack.

---

# Interview One-Liner

Flood Fill is a DFS/BFS traversal where we start from a source cell and replace all connected cells having the same original color with a new color.
